  <h3 class="c-left c-font-lowercase c-font-sbold">International</h3>

  <p>According to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) projections, a decrease on the global economy of 2.3% on 2023 and a rebound of 3.1% in 2024 is expected. Rising interest rates, as a way for the Central Banks to control the inflation and the conflict between Russian and Ukraine have been important factors for this slowdown. </p>

  <p>In this sense, the IMF expect global inflation decrease to 6.6% in 2023 (2.2 pp. less than 2022) and 4.3% in 2024. Those expectations have led to lower long-term interest rates and stimulated the financial markets in advanced and emerging economies.  </p>

  <p>In 2022, Latin America economy expanded by almost 4%, the employment rebound and the services sector was recovered from the COVID-19 pandemic. On the other hand, throughout January 2023, labor market in the US exceeded expectations with the lowest unemployment rate in five decades (3.4%), suggesting that the labor market has been resilient despite weaker macroeconomic dynamism. The progress in reducing inflationary pressures and the strengthen seen in the global labor markets, have given reasons to believe that central banks will control the inflation with less impact on the economic growth. </p>

