  <h3 class="c-left c-font-lowercase c-font-sbold">National</h3>

  <p>Although the Mexican economy faces a complex environment, given the inflation pressures and the dependence to the US economy, it still been dynamic by taking the investment opportunities offered by nearshoring. </p>

  <p>In this sense, in January the IMF has adjusted its growth expectations to 1.7%, due to the strength and resilience shown by the Mexican currency, which remains below MXN/USD 19, a level not seen since 2018; this adjust has been replicated by other institutions such as the Secretariat of Finance and Public Credit (Secretaria de Hacienda y Credito Publico, “SHCP” for its Spanish acronym), even private banks as Bank of America, Banorte and BBVA Mexico, which have improved their growth perspectives for the country to 2023.  </p>

  <p>The World Bank projects that the Mexican economy will grow by 0.09%, as result of the possible decrease in the economic dynamism of United States, which could affect exports and remittances. Regarding the price increases, Mexican Central Bank (Banxico for its Spanish acronym) continue to take restrictive measures, increasing the interest rates to control the high inflation environment in the country; it is expected the interest rates continue increasing up to 11.50%.  </p>


